    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. so you mentioned a capacitor. what exactly does a capacitor do in the unit and how would i tell if it's actually the problem or if it's just something stuck in the fan? looks like nothing is actually blocking it though.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The capacitor acts as an electrical \"jump start\" that creates the initial torque needed to spin the motor, similar to how a fuse hose on a car allows an engine to fire. To check if it's the culprit, listen for a loud whine when you power the unit on (indicating the motor is trying to start but failing) versus a complete hum that never overrides the sound; you can also try swapping in a known-good capacitor, but only after ensuring the power is completely disconnected to avoid severe electric shock. Since you've ruled out physical obstructions, a failed capacitor is usually the most likely cause preventing the blades from moving.",
      "source": "target",
